<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ861217-0196 </DOCNO><HL> South Korea Sees GrowthIn Economy of 8% in 1987</HL><DD> 12/17/86</DD><SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><IN> FRESTMONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON) </IN><DATELINE> SEOUL, South Korea  </DATELINE><TEXT>   The South Korean government, citing favorable world trade conditions, introduced a plan that calls for economic growth in 1987 of 8% and a current account surplus of $5 billion.    The economic planning minister, Kim Mahn Je, said the 8% growth in inflation-adjusted gross national product would follow an estimated surge of 12% this year and a 5.1% expansion in 1985. In addition to calling for 1987 growth of 8%, the five-year economic plan that starts next year envisions average GNP expansion of more than 7% annually.    The projected current account surplus for next year would follow an estimated $4.5 billion surplus this year. The current account comprises trade in goods and services and some unilateral transfers. </TEXT></DOC>